The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Business | Business Briefs
                                                                                                                           6                                                                                      Business Briefs
                              
	 Dhaka, May 16: Nitol-Niloy Group, which markets commercial vehicles of the Tata brand in Bangladesh, is planning to set up a 1,000MW power plant in the country in a joint venture with the Indian conglomerate, The Daily Star has reported. The local partner will conduct a feasibility study for setting up a coal-based power plant for the Tata management.                            
	 New Delhi, May 16: DLF plans to raise Rs 2,700 crore this fiscal through the sale of non-core assets to reduce its debt of over Rs 16,421 crore by about one-third. The company plans to cut its debt by Rs 5,000 crore, of which it plans to raise Rs 2,700 crore from the sale of non-core assets and the rest from internal accruals.                             
	 Mumbai, May 16: Air India has clocked a 16.7 per cent growth in the number of passengers in the first half of May compared with the year-ago period on the back of an increase in demand and summer holiday bookings.                             
	 New Delhi, May 16: The UPA government has got seven out of 10 for its performance from industry, a survey conducted by Assocham showed. Corporate houses, however, remained critical of the lack of consensus on divestment and high inflation.                             
	 New Delhi, May 16: The government is likely to seek public comments for liberalising foreign direct investment (FDI) in the retail and defence sectors next week. It will float six concept or discussion papers on FDI related norms.                                                                                                                          
